Info

Paper: Carryover Effects on Reproduction Can Buffer Against Mortality-Driven Population Declines at Elevated Developmental Temperatures

Authors: Noah T. Leith, Anthony Macchiano, Brigitte Tenhumberg, Inaya Smith, Jake P. Woods, Kasey D. Fowler-Finn

Date: November 11, 2025

Link: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/ele.70264

Notes

This paper does advanced modeling and statistics on mating carryover effects based on different temperatures that is beyond an introductory level. But it also includes measurement of treehoppers under two different development temperatures. Three scenarios are seen in Figure 3 of the paper copied here. You an also compare measurements of males and females for a given development temperature or an ANOVA for all four cases. The data included is a subset of the variables provided by the paper. Here are the anatomy measured included in the data file:

  • Anatomy: The anatomy measured includes the following:
    • f.ovi1 Female ovipositor trait 1 (length; m - micrometer).
    • f.ovi2 Female ovipositor trait 2 (width; m).
    • m.aed1 Male aedeagus trait 1 (m).
    • m.aed2 Male aedeagus trait 2 (m).
    • m.aed3 Male aedeagus trait 3 (m)
    • Pronotum Pronotum length (m).
    • Femur Leg III femur length (m).
    • Face Face width (m).
Uses
  • 2 sample t-test: Compare any of the 8 measurements for the two development temperature groups. Compare males and females for a given development temperature.
  • ANOVA: Compare the four groups of males and females and the two developmental temperatures.
  • Graphs: Reproduce the graphs in the top of Figure 3 and boxplots comparing the groups tested above.
  • Data science - wrangle: The data is in long format and can be used for assignments subsetting the data and obtaining summary information.
